      {
         "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Me? Why not us?</b><br /><br />After years of disunity, China (Zhongguo 中國) was once again unified, but that is only one step. After that, there is the need to keep the nation united.<br /><br />Among the great Buddhist teachings is the concept of “no-I”, which allows for a broader understanding of ourselves (<htcite0>) and even of a nation.<br /><br />Could Buddhist teachings have helped maintain the unification of the nation?<br /><br />If, instead of that teaching, a vision based on the existence of enemies — an “other” as evil — had been adopted, would it have been more difficult to maintain unity?</div></div></center></p>",
         "source": [
            {
               "type": 2,
               "uuid": "7667294c-8990-467c-be8c-38ef02e17b70",
               "text": "The Buddhist Society",
