                           "year": "541",
                           "month": "",
                           "day": ""
                        }
                     ],
                     "isTable": false,
                     "imgdesc": "",
                     "format": "markdown",
                     "PostMention": ""
                  },
                  {
                     "text": "<ul class=\"citation\"><li><i>\"...When Wendi (Yang Jian) was born in a convent [Zhixan], Taizu (Yang Zhong, father of Wendi) said, 'This son is protected by the Buddha of Heaven...'</i></li> </ul>",
                     "source": null,
                     "date_time": null,
                     "isTable": false,
                     "imgdesc": "",
                     "format": "html",
                     "PostMention": ""
                  },
                  {
                     "text": "Until the age of 13, he was raised by a Buddhist nun, after which he attended a school for nobles (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nBy the age of 14, he began to rise rapidly in the service of the future rulers of northern China (Zhongguo 中國).(<htcite2>).\n\n#### Rise to power\n\nAfter the death of the Northern Zhou emperor at only 35 years old, doubts arose regarding his successor. With this, Yang Jian (楊堅), his wife, and his collaborators decided that he should assume the throne. After overcoming several revolts, he finally established the Sui dynasty (隋代) on <htdate0>, assuming the title of Emperor Wendi (隋文帝) (aka Wen or Wenti) (<htcite3>; <htcite4>; <htcite5>).",
                     "source": [
                        {
                           "type": 1,
                           "uuid": "9d5ff2be-676d-403a-8f87-20e26614285c",
                           "text": "Xiong, V. C.",
                           "page": "pp. 153",
                           "date_time": {
